# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: channel-fleet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] The **10th Cruiser Squadron**, also known as **Cruiser Force B** was a formation of cruisers of the British Royal Navy from 1913 to 1917 and then again from 1940 to 1946.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron was established in July 1913 and allocated to the Third Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] In July 1914 it was reassigned to the new Grand Fleet, the squadron was also made *Cruiser Force B* in August 1914 but was more famously known as the Northern Patrol.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] It remained with the Grand Fleet until December 1917.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] On 22 March 1937 the Admiralty announced the temporary formation of the squadron for the coronation fleet review by King George VI on 20 April 1937.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron was commanded by Rear-Admiral Arthur Dowding.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron reformed in September 1940 and attached to the Home Fleet for the duration of the Second World War until September 1945.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] On 27 December 1942, it was engaged at the Battle of the Barents Sea as **Force R.** On 22 December 1943 the squadron was involved in the Battle of the North Cape where it was called **Force 2**.
[src:channel-fleet/10th-cruiser-squadron] In October 1946 the squadron was renamed the 2nd Cruiser Squadron and assigned to the Mediterranean Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] The **11th Cruiser Squadron** and also known as **Cruiser Force E** was a formation of cruisers of the British Royal Navy from 1914 to 1917 and again from 1939 to 1940.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron was first formed in July 1914 and was attached to the Third Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] In August 1914 it was reassigned to the Channel Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] It was designated Cruiser Force E for service off the west coast of Ireland and was dispersed by January 1915.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron reformed in October 1939 when the 12th Cruiser Squadron of the Northern Patrol was re-designated 11th Cruiser Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] It was then transferred under the control of the Commander-in-Chief, North Atlantic at Gibraltar until it was disbanded in 1940.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] Throughout the period the squadron was commanded by Commodore Richard J.R.
[src:channel-fleet/11th-cruiser-squadron] Scott, holding the appointment of Commodore Commanding, 11th Cruiser Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/12th-cruiser-squadron] The **12th Cruiser Squadron** also known as **Cruiser Force G** was a formation of cruisers of the British Royal Navy from 1914 to 1915 and then again from 1939 to 1943.
[src:channel-fleet/12th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron was first formed 1 August 1914 and was initially assigned to the Channel Fleet as *Cruiser Force G* patrolling the western Channel until February 1915.
[src:channel-fleet/12th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron was then reassigned to the Grand Fleet where it remained before being disbanded in February 1915.
[src:channel-fleet/12th-cruiser-squadron] The squadron reformed in August 1939 initially part of the Northern Patrol of the Home Fleet based at Scapa Flow but was re-designated 11th Cruiser Squadron in October 1939.
[src:channel-fleet/12th-cruiser-squadron] It re-formed as part of the Mediterranean Fleet in July 1942.
[src:channel-fleet/12th-cruiser-squadron] It was reassigned from 29 January 1943 to 2 July 1943 when it became a component of Force H and again from 1 October 1943 to December 1943.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] The **First Cruiser Squadron** was a Royal Navy squadron of cruisers that saw service as part of the Grand Fleet during World War I, then later as part of the Mediterranean during the Interwar period and World War II.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] It was first established in 1904 and existed until 1952.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] The squadron was formed in December 1904 when Cruiser Squadron was re-designated the 1st Cruiser Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] In March 1909, then consisting of battlecruisers, it was assigned to the 1st Division of the Home Fleet until April 1912.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] When the First World War began, the squadron was assigned to the Mediterranean Fleet where it participated in the pursuit of the German battlecruiser SMS *Goeben* and the light cruiser SMS *Breslau*.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] It joined then Grand Fleet in January 1915 where it participated in the battles of Dogger Bank and the Battle of Jutland.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] It was disbanded after the battle as three of its four ships had been sunk in June 1916.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] Ships *Courageous*, *Glorious* and *Furious* were detached from the 3rd Light Cruiser Squadron and named the First Cruiser Squadron, part of the newly formed Light Cruiser Force.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] It remained part of Light Cruiser Force until April 1919 when it was once again disbanded.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] In October 1924 the 1st Light Cruiser Squadron was re-designated the 1st Cruiser Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] This took effect in November 1924 and the squadron was reformed as an enlarged unit of the Mediterranean Fleet under the command of Rear Admiral Arthur Waistell.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] In June 1942 the squadron under the commander of Rear-Admiral Louis Keppel Hamilton was assigned to provide distant cover for Convoy PQ 17.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] The squadron consisted of the British cruisers HMS *London* (flagship) and *Norfolk*, the American cruisers USS *Wichita* and *Tuscaloosa* and four destroyers, two from the United States Navy.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] Louis Mountbatten served as commander of the squadron in the Mediterranean Fleet after the war.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-cruiser-squadron] Having been granted the substantive rank of vice admiral on 22 June 1949, Mountbatten became Second-in-Command of the Mediterranean Fleet in April 1950.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] The **1st Destroyer Flotilla**, also styled as the **First Destroyer Flotilla**, was a naval formation of the British Royal Navy from 1909 to 1940 and again from 1947 to 1951.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] In May 1906, the First Destroyer Flotilla was attached to the Channel Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] The flotilla was attached alongside the 2nd and 3rd Destroyer Flotillas.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] Between February and August 1907, it was stationed in Portsmouth until being reassigned to the Channel Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] In February 1909 the flotilla was transferred to the 1st Division of the Home Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] On 27 July 1909, it was placed under the command of Commodore Edward F.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] From May 1912 to July 1914 the flotilla was allocated to the First Fleet of the Home Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] At the outbreak of war in July, 1914, the First Destroyer Flotilla was part of the First Fleet and was composed of 20 destroyers, 1 depot ship, and 1 scout cruiser.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] In August 1914 it was grouped with two other flotillas to form the Harwich Force as part of the Grand Fleet, under the command of Reginald Tyrwhitt, until November 1916.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] The flotilla was next assigned to the Harwich Force where it remained until April 1917.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] From May 1917 until December 1918 it was in the Portsmouth Command.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] After World War One the flotilla was assigned to the Atlantic Fleet from November 1918 to April 1925.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] In 1925 it was re-designated 5th Destroyer Flotilla and assigned to its first overseas station as part of the Mediterranean Fleet until 1932.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] It was renamed back to the 1st Destroyer Flotilla still with the Med Fleet until August 1938.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] At the beginning of World War Two in September 1939, the flotilla was placed under the command of the Rear-Admiral, Destroyer Flotillas Mediterranean Fleet where it remained until July 1940 when it was moved to the Portsmouth Command, till May 1945.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] Post the Second World War the Flotilla was reformed again as part of the Mediterranean Fleet in July 1945 until October 1951 when it was renamed 1st Destroyer Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] Command structure organizational changes took place within the Royal Navy during the post-war period.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] The term Flotilla was previously applied to a tactical unit until 1951 which led to the creation of three specific Flag Officers, Flotillas responsible for the Eastern, Home and Mediterranean fleets.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] The existing destroyer flotillas were re-organized now as administrative squadrons.
[src:channel-fleet/1st-destroyer-flotilla] In the Royal Navy, a Captain (D) afloat or Captain Destroyers afloat is an operational commander responsible for the command of destroyer flotilla or squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] The British **3rd Destroyer Flotilla**, also styled as **Third Destroyer Flotilla**, was a naval formation of the Royal Navy from 1909 to 1939 and again from 1945 to 1951.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] In 1907 the Channel Fleet had a large Channel Flotilla of destroyers in February 1909 when it was divided to form the 1st and 3rd Destroyer Flotillas.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] From March 1909 to May 1912 the formation was part of the Nore Division, 3rd Division Home Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] In May 1912, the Home Fleet was split into the First Fleet, with ships in full commission, and the Second and Third Fleets, composed of ships partly crewed and laid up in reserve respectively.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] The 3rd Destroyer Flotilla remained part of the First Fleet until July 1914.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] On the outbreak of the First World War, the First Fleet became the Grand Fleet, and the 3rd Destroyer Flotilla joined the newly formed Harwich Force.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] In the summer of 1915 it was renumbered the 9th Destroyer Flotilla.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] It was reformed again from March 1918 as part of the Grand Fleet till November 1918.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] After the War the Flotilla joined the Atlantic Fleet, forming part of that organisation from December 1918 until August 1923.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] It was then allocated to the Mediterranean Fleet until 1926 when it was temporarily assigned to the China Station until 1927.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] It returned to the Mediterranean until 1938.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] By the beginning of World War Two in September 1939 it was still in the Mediterranean Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] It was re-allocated to the Home Fleet in October 1939 to November 1944 under the command of the Rear-Admiral, Destroyer Flotillas Home Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] The flotilla was sent back to join the Mediterranean Fleet in November 1944.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] Throughout this period the term Flotilla had applied to a tactical unit.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] In 1951, instead, three specific Flag Officers, Flotillas, were created responsible for escorts up to cruisers for the Eastern, Home and Mediterranean fleets.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] The previous destroyer flotillas were redesignated squadrons, and thus the 3rd Destroyer Flotilla became the 3rd Destroyer Squadron in July 1951.
[src:channel-fleet/3rd-destroyer-flotilla] The commander of the 3rd Destroyer Flotilla held the title of Captain (Destroyers), or 'Captain (D)'.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] The **5th Battle Squadron** was a squadron of the British Royal Navy consisting of battleships.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] The 5th Battle Squadron was initially part of the Royal Navy's Second Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] During the First World War, the Home Fleet was renamed the Grand Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] In August 1914, the 5th Battle Squadron was based at Portland, and consisted of a number of pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] Following the loss of HMS *Bulwark* in 1914, HMS *Lord Nelson* and *Agamemnon* were transferred from the 6th Battle Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] With the commissioning of the five fast battleships of the *Queen Elizabeth* class, the remaining pre-dreadnoughts were sent to the Mediterranean.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* herself was delayed in joining the squadron, instead taking part in the Dardanelles Campaign until May 1915.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] In 1916, the 5th Battle Squadron—under the command of Rear Admiral Hugh Evan-Thomas— was temporarily transferred to David Beatty's Battlecruiser Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] On 31 May, four ships of the Squadron served with distinction in the battle of Jutland.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] In the clash with the German I Scouting Group under Admiral Franz von Hipper, the 5th Battle Squadron "fired with extraordinary rapidity and accuracy" (according to Reinhard Scheer), damaging the battlecruisers SMS *Lützow* and *Seydlitz* and a number of other German warships.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] Three of the *Queen Elizabeth*s received hits from German warships during the engagement, yet they all returned home, though *Warspite*—whose steering was jammed—was targeted by the German line, taking 15 hits.
[src:channel-fleet/5th-battle-squadron] After the battle, HMS *Queen Elizabeth*—which had missed the battle due to being in dock—rejoined the squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The **Channel Fleet** and originally known as the **Channel Squadron** was the Royal Navy formation of warships that defended the waters of the English Channel from 1854 to 1909 and 1914 to 1915.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] Throughout the Royal Navy's history there had been different squadrons stationed in home waters.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] One of the earliest known naval formations to be based at Plymouth was called the Western Squadron which was the forerunner of the Channel Squadron that was later known as the Channel Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] In 1650 Captain William Penn, Commander-in-Chief, was charged with guarding the Channel from Beachy Head to Lands End with six ships.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] This system continued following the Restoration.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] It was the start of what was to become a Western Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] From 1690 the squadron operated out of Plymouth Dockyard during wartime periods, which was for most of the 18th century and early 19th century.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] In 1854 The Channel Squadron, sometimes known as the Particular Service Squadron, was established.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The Channel Squadron only became a permanent formation in 1858.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] During the 19th century, as the French developed Cherbourg as a base for steam-powered ships, the Royal Navy developed Portland Harbour as a base for the fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The harbour was built between 1849 and 1872 when the Royal Navy created a breakwater made of blocks from local quarries on the Isle of Portland.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] With the amelioration of Anglo-French relations, and the German challenge towards 1900, the need for a Channel Formation diminished and the main European naval arena shifted to the North Sea.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] Admiral Sir Arthur Wilson was officially "Senior Officer in Command of the Channel Squadron" from 1901 to 1903.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] His subordinate flag officer in that squadron was the Second-in-Command, who commanded a division of battleships.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] For the period 1858 to 1903 the Channel squadron was often incorrectly referred to as the Channel Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] On 17 April 1903 Lord Charles Beresford was appointed Vice-Admiral Commanding, Channel Squadron.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] On 6 May 1903 Admiral Beresford was informed by the Admiralty "that for the future the Channel Squadron shall be known as the Channel Fleet." On 14 December 1904 the Channel Fleet was re-styled the 'Atlantic Fleet' and the Home Fleet became the 'Channel Fleet'.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] On 24 March 1909, under a fleet re-organisation, the Channel Fleet became the 2nd Division of the Home Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] Of note:*As the Channel Squadron - renamed The Channel Fleet, September, 1901*.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] Of note: On 8 August 1914, ships from the pre-war Second and Third Fleets were organised into the Channel Fleet.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The Channel Fleet features in several historical novels about the Royal Navy, notably *Hornblower and the Hotspur* by C.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] Forester, in which Forester's fictional hero becomes a favourite of the real Channel Fleet commander, Admiral William Cornwallis.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The fleet also features in several of the Aubrey–Maturin novels by Patrick O'Brian.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The novel *Billy Budd* by Herman Melville is set on board ships of the Channel Fleet, in the immediate aftermath of the Spithead and Nore mutinies of 1797.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] In the novel *The War of the Worlds*, the Channel Fleet protects the huge mass of refugee ships escaping from the Essex coast in the face of the Martian onslaught.
[src:channel-fleet/channel-fleet] The initial heroic fight of HMS *Thunder Child* and the subsequent general engagement, is detailed in the chapter entitled "The Thunderchild".
